---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import Sidenote from '../components/Sidenote.astro';
import HoverCard from '../components/HoverCard.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
	title="Paul Diaz Ashot"
	description="Founder-operator. Founding team at GMX. Active Claude developer. London / Barcelona / New York."
>
	<main class="essay">
		<div class="essay-content">
			<header class="essay-header">
				<h1>Paul Diaz Ashot</h1>
				<div class="locations">London, Barcelona, New York</div>
				<div class="contact">
					<a href="mailto:paul.ashot@icloud.com">paul.ashot@icloud.com</a> ·
					(646) 996 5037 ·
					@supersonicsines
				</div>
				<div class="work-auth">Right to work: UK, US, EU</div>
			</header>

			<p class="lede">
				<em>[LEDE PLACEHOLDER]</em> This page is the long version of my CV. The PDF
				is the conventional summary; this is the network of pieces the summary points
				at. The hiring manager who scans should leave in sixty seconds with a clear
				signal; the curious reader who chases the threads should find substance under
				every link.
			</p>

			<Section title="Now" id="now">
				<p>
					I'm currently building <HoverCard term="Pawlymarket">
						<span class="hc-p">
							<em>[PAWLYMARKET HOVER-CARD PLACEHOLDER — 150 words]</em> A live scraper
							and statistical-arbitrage layer over prediction markets. Reached
							$50K ARR within two months of launch. The site reads order books
							across Kalshi, Polymarket, and a handful of smaller venues, looks
							for systematic mispricings, and surfaces them as actionable calls
							to a small subscriber base. The interesting engineering is in the
							scrape-aggregator architecture and the statistical modelling layer
							that ranks edges by expected value adjusted for liquidity.
						</span>
						<span class="hc-p further-reading">
							→ <a href="https://pawlymarket.com">pawlymarket.com</a> · dashboard
							screenshot inline · live P&amp;L attribution
						</span>
					</HoverCard>, a prediction-market analytics platform that's live and revenue-generating.
					Alongside it, I run a <Sidenote id="vinted" term="Vinted-to-Depop reselling agent">
						<em>[VINTED-DEPOP SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 75 words]</em> An end-to-end
						autonomous fashion-arbitrage agent operating across Vinted and Depop.
						Driven by Claude through a Telegram interface; sources items, calculates
						margins, lists, fulfills. Generated low-five-figure GMV before I throttled
						it for tax reasons.
					</Sidenote> and a Claude-powered <Sidenote id="booking" term="intelligent booking system">
						<em>[BOOKING SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> Agentic scheduler for
						a small local business. Takes class bookings, reschedules around capacity
						constraints, and organises future classes based on predicted demand. Lives
						as a deployed Claude tool with a Stripe integration.
					</Sidenote>. The arc is: applying current-frontier AI to small, real markets where
					I can be the operator and the engineer at once.
				</p>

				<p>
					The work runs along two threads. One is <Sidenote id="inventory" term="inventory automation">
						<em>[INVENTORY SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> Backend pipelines
						that keep listings, stock, and pricing synchronised across marketplaces
						without human review. The unsexy half of e-commerce that, when working,
						is invisible.
					</Sidenote> across reselling channels; the other is <Sidenote id="email" term="email triage">
						<em>[EMAIL TRIAGE SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> A Claude-based
						classifier that drafts replies, escalates urgent threads, and snoozes
						the rest. Built it for myself; would happily ship it as a product.
					</Sidenote> for the operations side. Both started as personal pain points and turned
					into running systems.
				</p>
			</Section>

			<Section title="GMX" id="gmx">
				<p>
					From 2020 to 2023 I was on the founding team at <HoverCard term="GMX">
						<span class="hc-p">
							<em>[GMX HOVER-CARD PLACEHOLDER — 200-300 words]</em> GMX is a decentralised
							perpetual exchange that scaled to $450M+ TVL and $40M+ annualised
							revenue with a team of three. Built originally as Gambit on the Binance
							Smart Chain, then re-architected and rebranded to GMX on Arbitrum
							and Avalanche. The core innovation was a unified liquidity pool (GLP)
							that backed all open positions, paying LPs a share of trading fees
							and funding rate.
						</span>
						<span class="hc-p">
							My role was growth and partnerships. I closed and co-closed integrations
							with Chainlink, Avalanche, and Frax; ran the institutional channel;
							sourced the bulk of professional liquidity in our first year on Arbitrum;
							and coordinated the Gambit → GMX rebrand and outreach.
						</span>
						<span class="hc-p further-reading">
							→ <a href="https://gmx.io">gmx.io</a> · DeFiLlama TVL chart · Bankless
							/ Decrypt coverage
						</span>
					</HoverCard>. Three of us, no outside investment, top-decile DeFi revenue generator
					during my tenure.
				</p>

				<p>
					I closed and co-closed strategic partnerships with <Sidenote id="chainlink" term="Chainlink">
						<em>[CHAINLINK SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The Chainlink BUILD
						programme integration gave us oracle pricing for the entire perpetuals
						book. Negotiated the grant component and the keeper-network configuration
						with Chainlink Labs.
					</Sidenote>, <Sidenote id="avalanche" term="Avalanche">
						<em>[AVALANCHE SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The Avalanche Rush
						deployment incentive was one of the single largest external capital injections
						into GMX, and the cross-chain expansion onto Avalanche roughly doubled
						our TVL within two months. Negotiated directly with the Ava Labs growth
						team.
					</Sidenote>, and <Sidenote id="frax" term="Frax">
						<em>[FRAX SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The Frax integration brought
						frxETH liquidity into GLP and gave us a proper stablecoin alternative
						to USDC. Co-designed the parameters with the Frax core team over a couple
						of weeks of technical back-and-forth.
					</Sidenote>, plus three smaller protocol integrations. I co-led the <HoverCard term="Gambit → GMX rebrand">
						<span class="hc-p">
							<em>[GAMBIT REBRAND HOVER-CARD PLACEHOLDER — 150-200 words]</em> The
							rebrand wasn't a marketing exercise; it was a chain migration. We
							were on Binance Smart Chain as Gambit and the product had hit a ceiling
							both technically and reputationally. The rebrand reframed the protocol,
							the migration moved liquidity to Arbitrum, and the launch landed cleanly
							because we'd lined up partners ahead of time.
						</span>
						<span class="hc-p">
							I owned the partner outreach component: Chainlink for oracles, Avalanche
							for the second deployment, Frax for stablecoin liquidity, plus the
							long tail of integrations and listings that needed to be in place
							at launch.
						</span>
					</HoverCard>, organising outreach and timeline across the partner network.
				</p>

				<p>
					Personally sourced $20M+ in cumulative capital deployments. Built and ran
					the institutional and community channels — 5,000+ Telegram members and direct
					relationships with eight-figure liquidity providers. The team exited at
					a <Sidenote id="exit" term="seven-figure exit">
						<em>[EXIT SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 30 words]</em> Crystallised proportionally
						to my equity. The dryness of this footnote is intentional.
					</Sidenote>.
				</p>
			</Section>

			<Section title="Before GMX" id="before">
				<p>
					<em>[BEFORE GMX FILLER]</em> I came to crypto from a longer arc that started
					in <Sidenote id="manchester" term="Manchester">
						<em>[MANCHESTER SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 75 words]</em> BSc Chemistry at
						the University of Manchester, 2018. The interesting work didn't happen
						in the lab; it happened in the trading-bot operation I ran in the basement
						of a friend's house in Fallowfield, scraping and arbitraging Steam item
						markets through several account-pool generations. First time I shipped
						code that made money while I slept.
					</Sidenote>, where I read chemistry and ran a small trading-bot operation
					on the side. The bots were what taught me to ship code that runs unattended.
				</p>

				<p>
					The intellectual lineage that mattered most ran from <HoverCard term="Wittgenstein">
						<span class="hc-p">
							<em>[WITTGENSTEIN HOVER-CARD PLACEHOLDER — 200 words]</em> The reading
							that mattered was the late Wittgenstein — <em>Philosophical Investigations</em>
							and the lectures on private language. The thing that hit me wasn't
							the famous formulation about meaning-as-use; it was the slower point
							underneath: that thinking is not what we do <em>before</em> language,
							it's something we do <em>in</em> language. That insight about thought
							being substrate-bound is also, almost identically, the insight behind
							language models.
						</span>
						<span class="hc-quote">
							"Philosophy is a battle against the bewitchment of our intelligence
							by means of language."
						</span>
						<span class="hc-p further-reading">
							→ <em>Philosophical Investigations</em>, Anscombe trans. · SEP entry
							on language games
						</span>
					</HoverCard> through to <Sidenote id="yudkowsky" term="Yudkowsky">
						<em>[YUDKOWSKY SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 75 words]</em> The early LessWrong
						sequences were the first place I encountered serious thinking about cognition
						as something to be engineered rather than studied. <em>The Sequences</em>
						and the AI-foom essays in particular set the frame for taking AI seriously
						as a domain ten years before everyone else did.
					</Sidenote>, by way of the LessWrong sequences. I read them in 2014 in a small
					flat in Manchester, and they reframed everything I'd absorbed about analytic
					philosophy as preparation for a different problem.
				</p>
			</Section>

			<Section title="Why Anthropic" id="why">
				<p>
					<em>[WHY ANTHROPIC FILLER — 2-3 paragraphs]</em> I want to work at Anthropic
					for the same reason I came to crypto in 2020: there's a small window where
					a category-defining product gets built by a small team, and the work isn't
					yet a commodity. I've spent the last three years using Claude in production
					and treating <Sidenote id="cai" term="Constitutional AI">
						<em>[CAI SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The CAI paper and the more
						recent work on character training. The aesthetic restraint of the approach
						— avoiding the human-feedback bottleneck without abandoning principles
						— is the thing that distinguishes Anthropic's outputs from the rest of
						the field for me.
					</Sidenote>, <Sidenote id="interp" term="interpretability">
						<em>[INTERPRETABILITY SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The interpretability
						team's work on superposition, dictionary learning, and the recent Claude-3-Sonnet
						feature extraction is, for my money, the most important applied research
						programme in AI right now.
					</Sidenote>, and <Sidenote id="mcp" term="MCP">
						<em>[MCP SIDENOTE PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> MCP changed my development
						process the day it shipped. The model-tool boundary becoming a clean
						protocol is the kind of small, correct architectural decision that compounds.
					</Sidenote> as living documents I've returned to repeatedly.
				</p>

				<p>
					What I bring is a founder's instinct for getting product into the hands
					of users who'll pay for it, attached to a working knowledge of where Claude
					genuinely wins and where the abstractions still leak. I've shipped six small
					production AI deployments in the last eighteen months. The next thing I
					want to do is ship them inside the company that builds the model.
				</p>
			</Section>

			<footer class="essay-footer">
				<a href="mailto:paul.ashot@icloud.com">paul.ashot@icloud.com</a> ·
				@supersonicsines ·
				<a href="/Paul_Diaz_Ashot_CV.pdf" download>Download CV (PDF)</a>
			</footer>
		</div>
	</main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
	.essay {
		max-width: 1000px;
		margin: 0 auto;
		padding: 64px 24px;
		position: relative;
		z-index: 1;
		counter-reset: sidenote;
	}

	.essay-content {
		max-width: 680px;
	}

	.essay-header {
		text-align: center;
		padding-bottom: 16px;
		border-bottom: 0.5px solid var(--color-rule);
		margin-bottom: 32px;
	}

	.essay-header h1 {
		margin: 0 0 8px 0;
		font-family: var(--font-serif);
		font-size: 36px;
		font-weight: 400;
		letter-spacing: 1px;
	}

	.locations {
		font-size: 16px;
		color: var(--color-ink);
		margin-bottom: 6px;
		letter-spacing: 0.5px;
	}

	.contact {
		font-family: var(--font-sans);
		font-size: 13px;
		color: var(--color-muted);
		margin-bottom: 4px;
	}

	.contact a {
		color: var(--color-ink);
	}

	.work-auth {
		font-style: italic;
		font-size: 13px;
		color: var(--color-muted);
	}

	.lede {
		font-size: 18px;
		line-height: 1.65;
		margin: 32px 0 16px 0;
	}

	.essay-content :global(p) {
		font-size: 18px;
		line-height: 1.65;
		margin: 0 0 16px 0;
	}

	.essay-content :global(a) {
		color: var(--color-ink);
		text-decoration: underline;
		text-decoration-color: var(--color-rule);
		text-underline-offset: 2px;
	}

	.essay-content :global(em) {
		font-style: italic;
	}

	.essay-content :global(b) {
		font-weight: 700;
	}

	.essay-footer {
		margin-top: 64px;
		padding-top: 24px;
		border-top: 0.5px solid var(--color-rule);
		text-align: center;
		font-family: var(--font-sans);
		font-size: 13px;
		color: var(--color-muted);
	}

	.essay-footer a {
		color: var(--color-ink);
	}

	@media (max-width: 768px) {
		.essay {
			padding: 40px 20px;
		}

		.essay-content :global(p) {
			font-size: 16px;
		}

		.lede {
			font-size: 16px;
		}
	}
</style>
